# Bella-Workflow Open Source License

Bella-Workflow adopts a dual licensing model, applying different licenses to the frontend components and other parts of the project.

## License Overview

1. Frontend Components: All components located in the web/ directory follow the licensing terms of the Dify project.

2. Other Components: Including the backend and other non-frontend components, which are licensed under the MIT License.

## Detailed License Terms

- For detailed license terms of the frontend components, please refer to the LICENSE_DIFY file.
  - Note: When using the frontend, you must not remove or modify the LOGO or copyright information in the Dify console or applications.
  - If you intend to use the frontend for multi-tenant services, please ensure you obtain written authorization from Dify.

- Other components are licensed under the standard MIT License.
  - The MIT License is a permissive license that allows free use, modification, and distribution of code, including for commercial purposes, as long as the original copyright notice and license text are retained.
  - For the official MIT License, see: https://opensource.org/licenses/MIT

## Contributor Notice

As a contributor, you agree that:

1. Project maintainers may adjust the open source license as needed.
2. Your contributed code may be used for commercial purposes.

## Bella-Workflow Additional Declarations

1. As a derivative project of Dify, Bella-Workflow inherits all licensing conditions and restrictions of Dify.

2. For any commercial use of Bella-Workflow, especially as a multi-tenant service, please comply with Dify's commercial licensing requirements and contact business@dify.ai for necessary authorization.

3. When using Bella-Workflow, this license file must be retained, and project documentation must clearly state that the project is based on Dify.

4. Contributors should agree that their contributed code may be used for commercial purposes.

